  "prompt": "Which is the best book for maths?",
  "response": "The best book for math can vary widely depending on your current level of understanding, interests, and the specific area of mathematics you're looking to explore. Here are some recommendations across different levels and topics:\n\n### For Beginners\n- **\"Mathematics: A Very Short Introduction\" by Timothy Gowers**: This offers a concise overview of the main concepts and ideas in mathematics.\n\n### High School Level\n- **\"The Art of Problem Solving\" series by Richard Rusczyk**: These books focus on problem-solving and are great for students looking to challenge themselves beyond standard curriculum.\n\n### College Level\n- **\"Calculus\" by Michael Spivak**: A rigorous introduction to calculus that helps develop a deep understanding of the concepts.\n- **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler**: A great book for understanding linear algebra without excessive reliance on determinants.\n\n### Advanced Topics\n- **\"Introduction to the Theory of Computation\" by Michael Sipser**: A foundational text in computer science that explores computational theory.\n- **\"Principles of Mathematical Analysis\" by Walter Rudin**: Often referred to as \"Baby Rudin,\" this is a classic text covering analysis.\n\n### Recreational Mathematics\n- **\"The Collected Papers of Paul Erd\u0151s\"**: A fascinating collection for those who enjoy the interplay between mathematics and culture.\n\n### Problem-Solving\n- **\"How to Solve It\" by George P\u00f3lya**: This classic book teaches problem-solving techniques and strategies.\n\n### Comprehensive Reference\n- **\"The Princeton Companion to Mathematics\" edited by Timothy Gowers**: A broad overview of many areas in mathematics, suitable for both beginners and advanced readers.\n\nUltimately, the \"best\" book for you will depend on your specific needs, so it may be helpful to explore a few and see which resonates with you!",
